{
  "answer": "**Charles Comte, *Traité de Législation: VOL III*, Chapter 48 (\"De la supériorité des peuples d’espèce caucasienne sur les peuples des autres espèces. — Des causes\").**[^1]\n\nComte counters the claim of innate racial inferiority—often tied to a supposed lack of genius among \"colored species\"—by first noting the existence of great minds like Epictetus, Phaedrus, and Terence among Roman slaves of the white race, then rhetorically questioning the absence of comparable figures among Negro slaves in Jamaica or Saint Lucia (who labor in sugar cultivation). He likens this demand to the fallacy of deeming U.S. citizens a \"degenerate race\" due to lacking classical Roman luminaries, quoting: \"to prove that the citizens of the United States are a degenerate race, for the reason that they have produced no orator like Cicero, or no poet like Virgil\".[^1]\n\n[^1]: Charles Comte, *Traité de Législation: VOL III*, [paragraph](/works/charles-comte-traite-de-legislation-vol-iii-ca589a/48-de-la-superiorite-des-peuples-d-espece-caucasienne/translation/#p-81116a).",
